document_title: Gnathostomiasis: Causes, symptoms, treatment and prevention
subsection_content: Gnathostomiasis is not transmitted from person to person. The life cycle of parasitic gnathostomiasis mainly occurs in dogs, pigs, cats, and wild animals (called hosts), while humans are infected by accidentally eating larvae found in food or water sources containing the disease. . In addition, in some rarer cases, people have gnarled head worms burrowing through the skin.

In addition, in some rarer cases, people have gnarled head worms burrowing through the skin.
